    "discriminators": [
     "Skiing, sledding or a shovel dragging: sustained contact with a GRANULAR medium. The signature is a continuous crunch — a dense micro-texture (very high onset_rate_per_second) rather than the smooth squeal of a hard-surface scrape, with a low crest_factor and a long sustain_ratio.",
     "Snow squeak (packed snow at low temperature) is the one place this can go quasi-tonal; the priors stay broad enough not to gate it out.",
     "Against ICE-FRICTION: the material axis. Ice scrapes are brighter (~3.8 kHz vs ~2.6 kHz), can ring or squeal, and have a wandering centroid; snow is darker, denser, granular and dead (decay ~10 ms, the shortest in the set).",
     "Against SNOW-MOVEMENT: FRICTION is a sustained surface drag; MOVEMENT is a slower, chunkier displacement of snow with resolvable strokes. Genuinely close — UCS overlaps them itself.",
     "Against SNOW-IMPACT: no discrete transient; sustained and low-crest."
    ],
