    "discriminators": [
     "Compacting a snowball is the purest CRUNCH in the taxonomy: a dense stochastic micro-texture of thousands of ice-grain fractures. Very high onset_rate_per_second, low crest_factor, near-zero ring — and quiet (low root_mean_square_level), because it is a hand-scale gesture.",
     "Level and duration are what separate it from SNOW-FRICTION and SNOW-MOVEMENT, which share the identical crunch texture at larger scale. UCS admits the SNOW-MOVEMENT overlap outright, so treat this as narrowable at best and let the filename commit.",
     "Against ICE-HANDLE: the material axis. Ice handling clinks and rattles (bright, high-crest, sparse); snow handling crunches (dark, low-crest, dense).",
     "Against SNOW-IMPACT: HANDLE has no dominant transient — it is texture without an event."
